# 1. Distributed web infrastructure

Whiteboard design of a three-server web infrastructure hosting
`www.foobar.com`: one load balancer in front of two identical application
servers, with a database Primary-Replica cluster.

## Diagram

```
                          ( User )
                              |
                www.foobar.com (A record -> LB public IP)
                              |
                       HTTP over TCP/IP
                              |
                              v
                  +-------------------------+
                  |   Load Balancer         |
                  |   HAProxy               |
                  |   (Round Robin)         |
                  +-----------+-------------+
                       /              \
                      /                \
                     v                  v
        +-------------------+   +-------------------+
        |     Server 1      |   |     Server 2      |
        |                   |   |                   |
        |  Nginx (web)      |   |  Nginx (web)      |
        |  App server       |   |  App server       |
        |  App files (code) |   |  App files (code) |
        |  MySQL (Primary)  |   |  MySQL (Replica)  |
        +---------+---------+   +---------+---------+
                  |                       ^
                  |   replication stream  |
                  +-----------------------+
            (Primary sends write log to Replica)
```

## Why each additional element is added

- **Load balancer (HAProxy):** distributes incoming traffic across the two
  servers so no single server is overwhelmed, and so the site keeps working if
  one server fails. It is the single public entry point.
- **Second server:** adds capacity (more requests handled in parallel) and
  redundancy (if one server dies, the other still serves traffic).
- **MySQL Primary-Replica cluster:** gives data redundancy and lets read
  queries be spread across nodes, improving read performance and availability.

## Specifics to explain

### Distribution algorithm
The load balancer is configured with the **Round Robin** algorithm. It forwards
each new request to the next server in the list, cycling back to the first
after the last. Server 1 gets request 1, Server 2 gets request 2, Server 1 gets
request 3, and so on — distributing the load evenly assuming servers have
similar capacity. (Other common algorithms include Least Connections and
Source/IP-hash.)

### Active-Active vs Active-Passive
This setup is **Active-Active**: both servers are running and actively
receiving traffic at the same time.

- **Active-Active:** all nodes handle requests simultaneously. Work is shared,
  giving more total capacity. The load balancer splits traffic across all live
  nodes.
- **Active-Passive:** only one node (active) handles traffic while the other
  (passive) stays on standby. The passive node takes over only if the active
  one fails (failover). It provides redundancy but not extra capacity during
  normal operation.

### How a Primary-Replica (Master-Slave) cluster works
The **Primary (Master)** node is the only one that accepts **write** operations
(INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE). Every change it makes is recorded in a binary log and
streamed to the **Replica (Slave)** node, which replays those changes to keep
an up-to-date copy of the data. The Replica is **read-only** from the
application's point of view and is typically used to serve **read** queries
(SELECT), spreading read load off the Primary.

### Difference between Primary and Replica regarding the application
- The application **writes** (and can read) only to the **Primary** node.
- The application **reads** from the **Replica** node (and the Primary), but it
  can **never write** to the Replica. The Replica receives its data exclusively
  through replication from the Primary, not directly from the application.

## Issues with this infrastructure

### Where are the SPOFs?
- **The load balancer** is a SPOF: there is only one. If it fails, no traffic
  reaches either server and the whole site is down.
- **The MySQL Primary** is effectively a SPOF for writes: if it goes down, no
  writes can happen until a Replica is promoted.

### Security issues
- **No firewall:** all ports/traffic are exposed; nothing filters or restricts
  who can reach the servers.
- **No HTTPS:** traffic is served over plain HTTP, so data between users and the
  infrastructure is unencrypted and can be intercepted (man-in-the-middle).

### No monitoring
There is no monitoring in place, so you cannot see performance, errors, load,
downtime, or attacks. Problems are discovered only when something visibly
breaks, making diagnosis and capacity planning very difficult.
